# Plan mode — the per-proposer drafter prompt. The final draft reuses the fusion
# panel, but a panel member otherwise gets NO system prompt (scry_run passes
# system=None), so an agentic coding CLI handed a bare task + a real repo + web would
# try to *do* the task — burn tool calls, attempt edits — instead of describing a
# plan. That is the root cause of the half-strength plan panel: opus churns tool calls
# to a 0-token timeout, codex/kimi waste turns on blocked writes, and agy (which has
# NO enforced read-only sandbox) can actually mutate the user's repo. This system
# prompt reframes each proposer as a plan AUTHOR and pins the read-only invariant by
# instruction for providers that can't enforce it via argv. Threaded through scry_run
# as `panel_system` (mirrors the aggregator_system override); normal runs leave it
# None so the panel stays general-purpose. Kept free of the substrings the
# interviewer/question-judge/synth/judge prompts use as routing anchors
# ("scope a task" / "deduplicating" / "plan drafts" / "impartial judge") so test
# stubs that key on the system prompt still distinguish the stages.
PLAN_DRAFTER_SYSTEM = (
    "Write the best possible implementation plan for the task in the request. Your only "
    "output is the plan itself — return it directly as "
    "GitHub-Flavored Markdown text. This work is READ-ONLY apart from writing that "
    "response: do NOT carry out the task and do not change anything — no creating, "
    "writing, editing, moving, or deleting files, and no running build, test, git, or "
    "other state-changing commands. You MAY read (files, the repository, the web) to "
